A length is measured with a flexometer and corrected to the reference temperature, $L_{20}=L_T[1+(\alpha-\beta)(20-T)]$, $L_T\approx800.074$ mm. Six contributions enter, all reduced to **base units (m, °C)**:
- instrument **bias** — Type B, expanded $3.7\ \mu$m at 95% on $n_d=4$ measurements (here treated already as a standard $u$ with $\nu=3$);
- reading **resolution** $1\ \mu$m — Type B rectangular, $a=0.5\ \mu$m;
- **reproducibility** — Type A, averaged over $n_r=5$;
- the workpiece/instrument **temperature coefficients** $\alpha,\beta$ — Type B rectangular from a handbook;
- the **temperature** $T=22\pm5$ °C — Type B (sensitivities $c_\alpha,c_\beta\approx\pm L_T\,\Delta T$, $c_T\approx -L_T(\alpha-\beta)$).

Summing the rows: $u^2(y)=1.3012\times10^{-11}\ \text{m}^2$, so $u(y)=3.607\ \mu$m. The **bias** ($\approx5.41\times10^{-12}$) and **reproducibility** ($\approx2.14\times10^{-12}$) dominate — that is where to improve the measurement.
